div.p:
II. That there are three Persons in the Godhead, the Father, the Son, and Holy Spirit;
                     Mat. 28.19. and that these three are One God,
                  1 Joh. 5.5. the same in Essence, equal in Power and Glory.

VIII. WE believe Man in his state of Innocency had freedom of Will to do good;


but by the Fall he hath utterly lost all that Power and Ability,
                     Ephes. 2.2, 3. being wofully depraved in all the Faculties of his Soul; there being in the Will and Mind of all naturally much Enmity against God,
                     Rom. 8.7. and a total aversion to him, and to every thing that is spiritually good;
                     Job 24.13. loving Darkness, and rebelling against the Light.

XVII. WE believe God requires Obedience of Man, and that the Rule of that Obedience is the moral Law as it is in the Hands of Christ;
                     Mich. 6.8. 1 Sam. 15.22. Rev. 2.14. Mat. 19.17 Mat. 22.37, 38, 39, 40. which teacheth all Persons their Duty to God, and to Man; the Sum of all being this, to love the Lord our God with all our Hearts, with all our Souls, and with all our Strength, and our Neighbours as our selves. And that tho the Law is abolished as a Covenant of Works, and as so considered, we are dead to it,
                  1 Joh. 3.4. Rom. 7.3, 4 and that dead to us; yet it remains as a Rule of Life and Righteousness for ever.


Eph. 5.19. Col. 3.16.XXVII. WE believe that singing the Praises of God, is a holy Ordinance of Christ, and not a part of Natural Religion, or a moral Duty only; but that it is brought under Divine Institution, it being injoined on the Churches of Christ to sing Psalms, Hymns, and spiritual Songs;
Acts 16.25 Heb. 2.12. Jam. 5.13. and that the whole Church in their Publick Assemblies (as well as private Christians) ought to sing God's Praises, according to the best Light they have received. Moreover, it was practised in the great Representative Church, by our Lord Jesus Christ with his Disciples,
Mat. 26.30 Mar. 14.26 after he had instituted and celebrated the Sacred Ordinance of his Holy Supper, as a commemorative Token of Redeeming Love.
